04643nam a22007095i 9780824864842DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20012001hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248648427 a10.1515/97808248648422doi  a(DE-B1597)484270  a(OCoLC)1076400112  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aDS890.B68bO3313 2001 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a952.04/0922211 aShiro, Okamoto, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Man Who Saved Kabuki :bFaubion Bowers and Theatre Censorship in Occupied Japan /cOkamoto Shiro. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTranslator’s Introduction -- tAuthor’s Introduction -- tChapter 1. Faubion Bowers and Japan, 1940 –1945 -- tChapter 2. Wartime Kabuki -- tChapter 3. The Occupation Commences and the Actors Return -- tChapter 4. Kabuki Censorship Begins -- tChapter 5. How Faubion Bowers “Saved” Kabuki -- tChapter 6. Kabuki’s Suffering Ends -- tChapter 7. Conclusion -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix A. A Kabuki Chronology, 1940–1948 -- tAppendix B. Kabuki Plot Summaries -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author and Translator0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs part of its program to promote democracy in Japan after World War II, the American Occupation, headed by General Douglas MacArthur, undertook to enforce rigid censorship policies aimed at eliminating all traces of feudal thought in media and entertainment, including kabuki. Faubion Bowers (1917-1999), who served as personal aide and interpreter to MacArthur during the Occupation, was appalled by the censorship policies and anticipated the extinction of a great theatrical art. He used his position in the Occupation administration and his knowledge of Japanese theatre in his tireless campaign to save kabuki. Largely through Bowers's efforts, censorship of kabuki had for the most part been eliminated by the time he left Japan in 1948. Although Bowers is at the center of the story, this lively and skillfully adapted translation from the original Japanese treats a critical period in the long history of kabuki as it was affected by a single individual who had a commanding influence over it. It offers fascinating and little-known details about Occupation censorship politics and kabuki performance while providing yet another perspective on the history of an enduring Japanese art form.Read Bowers' impressions of Gen. MacArthur on the Japanese-American Veterans' Association website.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aKabuki. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aLeiter, Samuel L.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082486484240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824864842423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824864842/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-066325-9  University of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK